<title type="html"><![CDATA[Metroid wram?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4894&amp;p=43683#p43683"><![CDATA[
I'm not sure on the technical difference of the terms 'PRG-RAM' / 'SRAM' / 'WRAM'.  As far as I can tell all 3 seem to be interchangable, with the possible exception being that SRAM is used to save data whereas PRG-RAM and WRAM don't, necessarily.<br /><br />Lots of NES games have additional RAM on cartridge because the NES has so little internally.  Games often just use it for additional workspace, and not necessarily to save games.  In order for SRAM to save games, it would need to be backed with a battery so that the RAM has a steady power source to keep it up when it's not in the NES.  Metroid probably didn't have a battery -- it probably only had the RAM.<br /><br />Metroid is also a port of an FDS game -- which <em>did</em> have saved games.  FDS games had a lot more space for RAM, and could save by writing data back to the floppy disk.<br /><br />Perhaps in the conversion to the cartridge, they ran out of RAM and didn't have enough left over to hold saved games.  Though I find this unlikely because a saved game in metroid can't be very big.<br /><br />That's a total guess though.  Maybe they just didn't want to shell out the extra money to put batteries in every cartridge.  Or maybe they didn't think to battery back RAM to save games back then (Metroid was a relatively early NES title).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=33">Disch</a> — Tue Feb 24, 2009 9:12 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
